Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Let me deliver the complete implementation plan.

---

# AI-Generated Custom Quote Pipeline: Implementation Plan

## Answering Your Design Questions First

### 1. Component Storage Format (`generated_component` column)

Use **option (a): store the source code as a string for reference only**. The actual serving happens via the registry file on disk. Do not use `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` with pre-rendered HTML — it would lose React interactivity (the Accept Quote button calls `acceptQuoteAction` as a server action and triggers `router.refresh()`), break the existing `QuoteActions` pattern, and create XSS surface area. The column is a developer convenience — a snapshot you can inspect in the DB without opening the filesystem.

### 2. Runtime Loading via Registry

The static registry approach is correct and is the right call for this codebase. Here is the honest tradeoff table:

| Factor | Registry approach | Dynamic `require()` / `fs.readFile` |
|---|---|---|
| Webpack/Turbopack compatibility | Full — static imports are tree-shaken and bundled at build time | Broken — bundler cannot statically analyze dynamic paths |
| Vercel deployment | Deploy once, works forever | Would need extra config or a runtime compiler |
| Type safety | Full — registry is typed | None |
| Adding a quote requires redeploy | Yes — acceptable for a developer-only workflow | No, but you'd trade bundler compatibility |
| Edge runtime compatible | Yes | No |

One important refinement: the registry should export a **typed interface** so the page and PDF route both import the same type, and the registry file should be kept in `src/generated-quotes/registry.ts` (inside `src/`) so TypeScript path aliases (`@/generated-quotes/registry`) work without extra tsconfig changes.

### 3. PDF for AI Quotes

Use **option (a): each quote has its own `QuotePDF.tsx`**, loaded via the same registry. Here is why: the whole premise of the AI pipeline is that each quote is *bespoke* — different structure, different emphasis, different sections. A single generic parser that consumes `raw_content` markdown and renders it would need to replicate all the layout intelligence you are asking Claude to generate per-quote. You would end up with a generic template that defeats the purpose. The per-quote `QuotePDF.tsx` file is small (100-150 lines of `@react-pdf/renderer`), and the AI generates it in the same pass as the web component. The registry holds both.

### 4. DB Insertion Script

Keep it as **a standalone `scripts/create-quote.ts`** called by the generation pipeline. Here is why: it keeps the Claude command self-contained (one command does the full job: generate files + insert DB row). Integrating it into a Server Action would require a running dev server during generation. The script uses the same `@libsql/client` singleton pattern already in `src/shared/lib/db.ts` and reads the same `DATABASE_URL` env var. This is exactly the pattern `scripts/seed-db.mjs` uses today.

---

## Complete File Map

### Files to Create (new)

```
src/generated-quotes/
  registry.ts                          ← Static registry, imported by page and PDF route
  .gitkeep                             ← Keep directory tracked (registry.ts IS committed)

src/app/[locale]/admin/quotes/
  page.tsx                             ← NEW: dedicated quotes list page

src/app/[locale]/admin/quotes/[id]/
  page.tsx                             ← NEW: admin preview of a specific AI quote

src/features/quotes/components/
  AiQuoteShell.tsx                     ← NEW: thin wrapper that handles accept/download chrome around generated content

scripts/
  create-quote.ts                      ← NEW: DB insertion script

.claude/commands/
  generate-quote.md                    ← NEW: Claude Code generation skill
```

### Files to Modify (existing)

```
src/shared/lib/db.ts                   ← Add new migrations to array
src/features/quotes/types/index.ts     ← Extend Quote interface
src/features/quotes/lib/queries.ts     ← Extend rowToQuote(), createAiQuote()
src/app/[locale]/quote/[id]/page.tsx   ← Branch on quoteType === "ai-generated"
src/app/api/quote/[id]/pdf/route.ts    ← Branch to registry QuotePDF for ai-generated
src/features/quotes/actions/index.ts   ← Add sendAiQuoteAction (or update sendQuoteAction)
src/app/[locale]/admin/page.tsx        ← Optionally: add link to /admin/quotes
src/messages/en.json                   ← Add new i18n keys
src/messages/es.json                   ← Add new i18n keys
```

---

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1: DB Schema — `src/shared/lib/db.ts`

Add two entries to the existing `migrations` array (do NOT touch the `CREATE TABLE` block — existing installs use ALTER TABLE for new columns):

```typescript
"ALTER TABLE quotes ADD COLUMN raw_content TEXT",
"ALTER TABLE quotes ADD COLUMN generated_component TEXT",
```

These go at the end of the array. The try/catch loop already handles "column already exists" errors.

### Step 2: Extend the `Quote` Type — `src/features/quotes/types/index.ts`

Extend the `QuoteType` union and the `Quote` interface:

```typescript
export type QuoteType = "line-items" | "blueprint" | "ai-generated";

export interface Quote {
  // ... all existing fields unchanged ...
  // New AI-generated fields
  rawContent?: string;
  generatedComponent?: string;
}
```

No changes needed to `CURRENCY_SYMBOLS`, `CURRENCY_LABELS`, or the calculation helpers.

### Step 3: Extend Queries — `src/features/quotes/lib/queries.ts`

Two changes:

**3a. Extend `rowToQuote()`** — add at the end of the returned object:
```typescript
rawContent: (row.raw_content as string) || undefined,
generatedComponent: (row.generated_component as string) || undefined,
```

**3b. Add `createAiQuote()` function** — a new focused function for the generation pipeline (the existing `createQuote()` is tied to `QuoteFormData` from Zod which doesn't have the new fields and would require a schema change that risks the admin form):

```typescript
export interface AiQuoteInput {
  clientName: string;
  clientEmail: string;
  clientCompany: string;
  title: string;
  currency: Quote["currency"];
  locale: Quote["locale"];
  validUntil: string;
  rawContent: string;
  generatedComponent: string;
  status?: Quote["status"];
}

export async function createAiQuote(data: AiQuoteInput): Promise<Quote> {
  const db = await ensureDb();
  const id = nanoid(10);
  const now = new Date().toISOString();

  await db.execute({
    sql: `INSERT INTO quotes (
            id, client_name, client_email, client_company, title,
            quote_type, currency, locale, valid_until,
            raw_content, generated_component,
            status, line_items, created_at, updated_at
          ) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, 'ai-generated', ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, '[]', ?, ?)`,
    args: [
      id,
      data.clientName, data.clientEmail, data.clientCompany, data.title,
      data.currency, data.locale, data.validUntil,
      data.rawContent, data.generatedComponent,
      data.status ?? "draft",
      now, now,
    ],
  });

  return (await getQuoteById(id))!;
}
```

### Step 4: Registry File — `src/generated-quotes/registry.ts`

This file starts empty and gets updated by the generation pipeline. It must always be valid TypeScript even when empty:

```typescript
// Auto-generated by .claude/commands/generate-quote.md
// Do not edit manually. Run the generate-quote command to add entries.

import type { ComponentType } from "react";
import type { Quote } from "@/features/quotes/types";

export interface QuoteRegistryEntry {
  QuoteContent: ComponentType<{ quote: Quote }>;
  QuotePDF: ComponentType<{ quote: Quote }>;
}

export const quoteRegistry: Record<string, QuoteRegistryEntry> = {
  // Entries are added here by the generation pipeline
  // Example: 'abc123xyz': { QuoteContent, QuotePDF }
};
```

When the pipeline runs for quote ID `abc123`, it appends an import and a registry entry:

```typescript
import { QuoteContent as QuoteContent_abc123 } from "./Quote_abc123/QuoteContent";
import { QuotePDF as QuotePDF_abc123 } from "./Quote_abc123/QuotePDF";

export const quoteRegistry: Record<string, QuoteRegistryEntry> = {
  'abc123xyz': { QuoteContent: QuoteContent_abc123, QuotePDF: QuotePDF_abc123 },
};
```

### Step 5: `AiQuoteShell` Component — `src/features/quotes/components/AiQuoteShell.tsx`

This is a thin "chrome" wrapper that adds the PRAGMA header, locale switcher, PDF download link, and Accept button around the bespoke `QuoteContent`. It preserves the existing `QuoteActions` + `acceptQuoteAction` pattern:

```typescript
"use client";

import type { Quote } from "../types";
import type { ComponentType } from "react";
import { QuoteActions } from "./QuoteViewer"; // extract this sub-component or duplicate it
import { useLocale } from "next-intl";
