## Risks and Gotchas

### Registry is committed code, not runtime data
The registry must be committed and deployed to Vercel for AI quotes to render. If you create a quote locally, test it, and forget to commit + deploy, production will hit the `notFound()` branch in the client page. The generation pipeline step 7 (summary output) should make this explicit. Consider adding a guard in development: if `NODE_ENV === "development"` and the registry has no entry for the id, show a more descriptive error.

### `QuoteContent` must be a Client Component
Because `AiQuoteShell` is a Client Component (it uses `useState` for the accepting state), any component rendered inside it as JSX is also treated as a client boundary. The generated `QuoteContent` should have `"use client"` at the top. If it is a Server Component without the directive, React will throw in production. Add this requirement explicitly in the `.claude/commands/generate-quote.md` instructions.

### `@react-pdf/renderer` and Server Components
The existing `next.config.ts` already has `serverExternalPackages: ["@react-pdf/renderer"]`. The generated `QuotePDF.tsx` files must never be imported in a client boundary — they are only used in the API route handler (`/api/quote/[id]/pdf/route.ts`), which runs server-side. The registry exports both `QuoteContent` and `QuotePDF` from the same object, but `QuotePDF` should only be accessed in server contexts. Document this clearly in the registry's JSDoc comment.

### `gray-matter` dependency for the script
The `create-quote.ts` script needs frontmatter parsing. `gray-matter` is the standard choice. If you want zero new dependencies, the script can instead require that frontmatter is passed as separate `--client-name`, `--title`, etc. flags. Either approach works — frontmatter parsing is simpler for the Claude command to drive.

### `nanoid` in the generation script vs. the DB
The script generates the ID and passes it to both the file path and the DB. Make sure the same ID is used for the directory name (`Quote_[id]`), the registry key, and the DB row. A mismatch between these three would cause a runtime error. The Claude command should generate the ID once in step 2 and reuse it consistently throughout all subsequent steps.

### `QuoteTable` needs a third type badge
The existing `QuoteTable.tsx` has explicit handling for `"blueprint"` vs. other types in the badge display. After adding `"ai-generated"` to the `QuoteType` union, update the table to show an "AI Custom" badge for this type. This is a one-line change in the ternary on lines 88-91 and 173-176.

### Admin route collision — `[id]/page.tsx` vs `[id]/edit/page.tsx`
The new `[id]/page.tsx` sits at the same level as the `[id]/edit/` directory — this is fine in Next.js App Router. `[id]/page.tsx` handles `/admin/quotes/abc123`, and `[id]/edit/page.tsx` handles `/admin/quotes/abc123/edit`. No conflict. Confirmed by looking at the current structure which already has the `edit` directory with no `page.tsx` at `[id]`.

### `sendQuoteAction` `revalidatePath` scope
The existing `sendQuoteAction` calls `revalidatePath("/[locale]/admin", "page")`. After the new admin routes exist, you may also need `revalidatePath("/[locale]/admin/quotes/[id]", "page")` and `revalidatePath("/[locale]/admin/quotes", "page")` if those pages should reflect the status change immediately without a full reload.

